1
00:00:00,269 --> 00:00:05,589
Trading is a game of deceptions and traps,
and you must learn to play accordingly.

2
00:00:05,589 --> 00:00:09,820
I learned this the hard way, with my own money.

3
00:00:09,820 --> 00:00:14,610
When you enter the trading game, one of the
first concepts you learn about is the moving

4
00:00:14,610 --> 00:00:15,610
averages.

5
00:00:15,610 --> 00:00:20,840
And for a good reason, moving averages represent
one of the most visually effective tools for

6
00:00:20,840 --> 00:00:22,620
scanning markets.

7
00:00:22,620 --> 00:00:29,510
Their simple concept of filtering out noise
and to identify trend biases appears compelling.

8
00:00:29,510 --> 00:00:34,430
Traders gravitate towards moving averages
because of their clean visual communication

9
00:00:34,430 --> 00:00:36,829
of uptrends and downtrends.

10
00:00:36,829 --> 00:00:43,420
When prices cross above or below these lines,
we get excited, it subconsciously triggers

11
00:00:43,420 --> 00:00:47,079
decisions, seeking confirmation of emerging
directions.

12
00:00:47,079 --> 00:00:52,390
In fact, one of the foundational rules of
technical analysis is the moving average breakout.

13
00:00:52,390 --> 00:00:57,810
And I can show you a lot of textbook examples
showing this principle in action.

14
00:00:57,810 --> 00:01:03,720
A moving average acting as dynamic support
turns to resistance once broken.

15
00:01:03,720 --> 00:01:10,610
And the previous line acting as resistance
morphed into perfect support on retest.

16
00:01:10,610 --> 00:01:14,250
It's the kind of signal every technical trader
lives for.

17
00:01:14,250 --> 00:01:16,880
We all took this kind of trade in the past.

18
00:01:16,880 --> 00:01:21,740
But as obvious as some of those patterns look
in hindsight, there is an important thing

19
00:01:21,740 --> 00:01:23,720
most people miss.

20
00:01:23,720 --> 00:01:30,650
Only a small percentage, maybe 15-20%, of
moving average breakouts actually play out

21
00:01:30,650 --> 00:01:34,140
as cleanly as the textbook examples.

22
00:01:34,140 --> 00:01:38,130
It all comes down to understanding how moving
averages work.

23
00:01:38,130 --> 00:01:43,180
A moving average shows the average price of
market over a period of time, like the last

24
00:01:43,180 --> 00:01:44,860
50 candles.

25
00:01:44,860 --> 00:01:49,930
Traders pay close attention to when the price
crosses above or below the moving average

26
00:01:49,930 --> 00:01:50,930
line.

27
00:01:50,930 --> 00:01:57,130
That's because it signals whether the trend
is turning from up to down or vice versa.

28
00:01:57,130 --> 00:02:02,570
But here's the thing - smart traders know
other traders are watching those moving averages

29
00:02:02,570 --> 00:02:03,570
too.

30
00:02:03,570 --> 00:02:09,560
So sometimes they'll push the price briefly
over or under the moving average, even if

31
00:02:09,560 --> 00:02:12,990
the main trend is still going the other way.

32
00:02:12,990 --> 00:02:18,790
Their goal is to trick people into thinking
the trend has changed, so those traders jump

33
00:02:18,790 --> 00:02:24,560
in - and then the big traders reverse the
price back where it came from, trapping those

34
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:27,370
followers with big losses.

35
00:02:27,370 --> 00:02:33,980
The reality is that the vast majority of moving
average breakouts end up being fakeouts or

36
00:02:33,980 --> 00:02:37,050
false breaks that fool traders.

37
00:02:37,050 --> 00:02:42,170
Just because the moving average is broken,
the new level doesn't guarantee anything about

38
00:02:42,170 --> 00:02:44,209
what comes next.

39
00:02:44,209 --> 00:02:49,620
More often than not, price action just wicks
through this zone, then continues the initial

40
00:02:49,620 --> 00:02:50,780
move.

41
00:02:50,780 --> 00:02:55,720
Some call these "false breakouts", others
see them as liquidity runs.

42
00:02:55,720 --> 00:03:01,311
And while they cause trouble for traders who
get trapped, if you spot them coming, you

43
00:03:01,311 --> 00:03:03,590
have a chance to profit.

44
00:03:03,590 --> 00:03:06,790
Those "false breakouts" can really mess with
your head.

45
00:03:06,790 --> 00:03:12,840
As I was losing most of my trades using this
signal, I started to understand why it happens

46
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:13,860
though.

47
00:03:13,860 --> 00:03:20,690
Common moving averages, like the 20, 50 or
200, are like battle zones between buyers

48
00:03:20,690 --> 00:03:24,050
and sellers pushing price both ways.

49
00:03:24,050 --> 00:03:30,840
So it makes sense the price action wavers
in and out sometimes before settling again.

50
00:03:30,840 --> 00:03:37,069
What really sunk in for me is that chasing
moving average breakouts after a strong trend

51
00:03:37,069 --> 00:03:41,760
is likely to lose money overall, especially
as a beginner.

52
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:47,910
Those massive explosive moves that seem so
easy to catch are actually pretty rare.

53
00:03:47,910 --> 00:03:54,129
And even if the break is real, actually hanging
on through volatility and exiting at the right

54
00:03:54,129 --> 00:03:56,690
time takes a lot of experience.

55
00:03:56,690 --> 00:04:03,220
I had a major breakthrough when I finally
grasped the concept of liquidity.

56
00:04:03,220 --> 00:04:08,989
Liquidity is all the orders that are stacked
up in the market waiting to be executed.

57
00:04:08,989 --> 00:04:14,450
Liquidity usually builds up on both sides
of the moving average, especially when there’s

58
00:04:14,450 --> 00:04:15,450
a breakout.

59
00:04:15,450 --> 00:04:21,260
This is because there are lots of traders
using similar entries and exits.

60
00:04:21,260 --> 00:04:26,940
Buyers who think the market's going up tend
to buy when price moves above a moving average,

61
00:04:26,940 --> 00:04:30,040
placing their stop losses below it.

62
00:04:30,040 --> 00:04:35,160
Sellers who think price is going down put
their stop losses above the moving average

63
00:04:35,160 --> 00:04:37,340
when price moves below it.

64
00:04:37,340 --> 00:04:43,320
And this is exactly why a lot of times moving
average breakouts don't have real buying or

65
00:04:43,320 --> 00:04:45,940
selling conviction behind them.

66
00:04:45,940 --> 00:04:53,130
And as soon as stops get taken out above or
below, prices whip right back the other way.

67
00:04:53,130 --> 00:04:58,970
That ends up leaving a bunch of trapped traders
who helped fuel the reversal with their stop

68
00:04:58,970 --> 00:05:00,130
losses.

69
00:05:00,130 --> 00:05:05,100
The momentum they provided can really move
the market away from the moving average in

70
00:05:05,100 --> 00:05:06,880
the opposite direction.

71
00:05:06,880 --> 00:05:12,389
During strong trends, it's smarter to wait
for these failed breakouts to happen before

72
00:05:12,389 --> 00:05:13,389
entering.

73
00:05:13,389 --> 00:05:17,810
The risk is way lower versus chasing the initial
moves.

74
00:05:17,810 --> 00:05:24,250
And the potential reward is way higher if
price bounces hard after squeezing those stop

75
00:05:24,250 --> 00:05:25,310
runs.

76
00:05:25,310 --> 00:05:27,810
Let me explain the strategy I use.

77
00:05:27,810 --> 00:05:31,240
The first thing I watch for is a strong trend.

78
00:05:31,240 --> 00:05:37,460
To me that means the price has been steadily
rising or falling for at least a couple days

79
00:05:37,460 --> 00:05:40,680
without reversing more than a few percent.

80
00:05:40,680 --> 00:05:46,280
You want to see higher highs, higher lows,
multiple breaks of structure and no major

81
00:05:46,280 --> 00:05:48,310
change of character.

82
00:05:48,310 --> 00:05:53,470
During these trends, institutional traders
have the market under their control and can

83
00:05:53,470 --> 00:05:56,020
manipulate prices more easily.

84
00:05:56,020 --> 00:06:01,060
Once a strong trend is in place, I'll monitor
the moving averages.

85
00:06:01,060 --> 00:06:06,320
Usually a 50-period is all I need, but you
can select any period you want, just make

86
00:06:06,320 --> 00:06:11,670
sure you use a common one, like the 20 or
200.

87
00:06:11,670 --> 00:06:17,960
I'm looking to see if the price crosses above
or below that average line, but stays there

88
00:06:17,960 --> 00:06:22,139
for only a very short time, only for a few
candles.

89
00:06:22,139 --> 00:06:25,669
That's a red flag it might be a false breakout.

90
00:06:25,669 --> 00:06:28,360
The next thing I check is volume.

91
00:06:28,360 --> 00:06:34,770
On a real trend change, you'd expect volume
to spike as more orders pile in.

92
00:06:34,770 --> 00:06:39,789
But with a false breakout, volume is often
lower than normal.

93
00:06:39,789 --> 00:06:44,310
That tells me not many people took the bait
of the fake signal.

94
00:06:44,310 --> 00:06:49,160
If I see a liquidity run, that’s the strongest
signal I can get.

95
00:06:49,160 --> 00:06:55,070
Armed with those signs, I'll enter a position
against the false breakout - so if it crosses

96
00:06:55,070 --> 00:07:01,590
above the moving average during a down trend,
I'll short the market, and vice versa.

97
00:07:01,590 --> 00:07:04,940
Let me give you an example to help explain
it better.

98
00:07:04,940 --> 00:07:10,740
In this chart, oil prices had been steadily
increasing on high demand.

99
00:07:10,740 --> 00:07:16,450
The 50-day moving average was rising strongly
in line with the uptrend.

100
00:07:16,450 --> 00:07:19,070
Multiple breaks of structure during this trend.

101
00:07:19,070 --> 00:07:25,810
And here, price dipped under the 50-period
average for just a couple of candles before

102
00:07:25,810 --> 00:07:28,160
rebounding right back above.

103
00:07:28,160 --> 00:07:33,350
Volume was surprisingly low for such a market-moving
event.

104
00:07:33,350 --> 00:07:36,949
And look at this liquidity run, below this
level.

105
00:07:36,949 --> 00:07:38,889
I call it a double trap.

106
00:07:38,889 --> 00:07:44,570
This move below the moving average trapped
price action traders, waiting for a break

107
00:07:44,570 --> 00:07:50,169
below this level, and at the same time, trapped
moving average traders.

108
00:07:50,169 --> 00:07:57,099
To me, it seemed like a false breakout designed
to attract short sellers before resuming the

109
00:07:57,099 --> 00:07:58,099
rally.

110
00:07:58,099 --> 00:08:03,400
Sure enough, prices had reversed all the way
back up, causing big losses for anyone who

111
00:08:03,400 --> 00:08:05,229
shorted the "breakdown".

112
00:08:05,229 --> 00:08:11,539
The smart play here was going long against
the fake signal, in line with the previous

113
00:08:11,539 --> 00:08:12,720
trend.

114
00:08:12,720 --> 00:08:16,169
On the flip side, there’s a similar situation.

115
00:08:16,169 --> 00:08:19,060
Price has been tanking for days.

116
00:08:19,060 --> 00:08:21,420
Multiple breaks of structure to the downside.

117
00:08:21,420 --> 00:08:24,200
Lower lows and lower highs.

118
00:08:24,200 --> 00:08:27,530
And the move above the 50-period line.

119
00:08:27,530 --> 00:08:33,380
Again, it was barely above for a few candles,
on lighter than usual volume.

120
00:08:33,380 --> 00:08:39,690
Observe the liquidity run, trapping another
group of buyers, to the upside.

121
00:08:39,690 --> 00:08:46,430
And of course, price reversed direction and
broke below the moving average once again,

122
00:08:46,430 --> 00:08:48,990
accelerating its fall further.

123
00:08:48,990 --> 00:08:56,399
The play here was going short against the
fake signal, once price moved below the 50

124
00:08:56,399 --> 00:08:57,500
SMA.

125
00:08:57,500 --> 00:09:01,610
It doesn’t matter the market you trade,
that’s the beauty of this strategy.

126
00:09:01,610 --> 00:09:08,130
Here gold prices had been making higher highs
and higher lows, in an upward trend, with

127
00:09:08,130 --> 00:09:12,430
the 50-day moving average reflecting the positive
momentum.

128
00:09:12,430 --> 00:09:17,360
Then, gold took a quick nosedive below the
moving average.

129
00:09:17,360 --> 00:09:20,920
We even had a liquidity run during this period.

130
00:09:20,920 --> 00:09:26,769
Despite the initial panic in the market, the
volume during this drop was notably lower

131
00:09:26,769 --> 00:09:29,750
than expected for a significant trend change.

132
00:09:29,750 --> 00:09:36,790
The correct trade was a long one, once price
moved above the 50 SMA.

133
00:09:36,790 --> 00:09:41,720
After a prolonged downward trend, a false
breakout presented an opportunity.

134
00:09:41,720 --> 00:09:48,420
The price briefly rose above the 50-day moving
average, moved past this level, that being

135
00:09:48,420 --> 00:09:52,820
a liquidity run, causing a stir among traders.

136
00:09:52,820 --> 00:09:58,640
We had low volume during this move, so long
positions were off the table.

137
00:09:58,640 --> 00:10:04,310
As price reversed direction and dipped back
below the moving average, that was the time

138
00:10:04,310 --> 00:10:08,890
to enter a sell position, in line with the
previous trend.

139
00:10:08,890 --> 00:10:15,490
In this recent trend where the market had
been climbing steadily, the 50-period moving

140
00:10:15,490 --> 00:10:17,150
average was on my radar.

141
00:10:17,150 --> 00:10:23,770
As price briefly dipped below the moving average
and registered also a liquidity run, this

142
00:10:23,770 --> 00:10:26,660
move caught the attention of many traders.

143
00:10:26,660 --> 00:10:31,000
But, the volume during this dip was surprisingly
low.

144
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:35,790
A textbook false breakout, trapping sellers
on the short side.

145
00:10:35,790 --> 00:10:41,120
And true enough, within the next candles,
the price bounced back above the moving average.

146
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:47,550
This was the ideal time to enter a long trade,
capitalizing on the trapped traders below

147
00:10:47,550 --> 00:10:49,620
the moving average.

148
00:10:49,620 --> 00:10:56,600
Here the market had been on a positive trajectory
for days, aligning well with the 50-day moving

149
00:10:56,600 --> 00:10:57,600
average.

150
00:10:57,600 --> 00:11:03,570
Then, out of the blue, the stock dipped below
the moving average, setting off alarm bells

151
00:11:03,570 --> 00:11:05,290
for many traders.

152
00:11:05,290 --> 00:11:10,550
Observe also this liquidity run and the low
volume during this dip.

153
00:11:10,550 --> 00:11:16,670
All our conditions were met: strong trend,
a move below the moving average, liquidity

154
00:11:16,670 --> 00:11:19,050
run and low volume.

155
00:11:19,050 --> 00:11:24,649
Fair enough, the stock swiftly climbed back
above the moving average, and that was the

156
00:11:24,649 --> 00:11:27,579
perfect moment to initiate a long trade.

157
00:11:27,579 --> 00:11:34,170
By recognizing the patterns of smart money
manipulating prices with false breakouts,

158
00:11:34,170 --> 00:11:36,620
you take the emotion out of the trade.

159
00:11:36,620 --> 00:11:41,720
You're not getting swept up by the crowd being
baited by a fake signal.

160
00:11:41,720 --> 00:11:47,500
Instead, you profit from the liquidity run
that inevitably follows.

161
00:11:47,500 --> 00:11:52,690
Some key aspects to remember:
Only trade these set-ups during strong trends,

162
00:11:52,690 --> 00:11:58,829
when major players have more control
Watch for breakouts that last only a short

163
00:11:58,829 --> 00:12:04,899
time, like a few candles
Check volume - it should be unusually light

164
00:12:04,899 --> 00:12:08,730
Take a tight stop in case it turns into a
real breakout

165
00:12:08,730 --> 00:12:15,589
It's an easy strategy, but it requires staying
cool-headed and trusting your analysis of

166
00:12:15,589 --> 00:12:17,500
the market structure.

167
00:12:17,500 --> 00:12:21,610
Don't get fooled by hype and focus on the
big picture trend.

168
00:12:21,610 --> 00:12:26,510
Pay attention to the signs of possible manipulation
by big money.

169
00:12:26,510 --> 00:12:32,870
When you spot a false breakout, get in position
to profit as the price retraces where it came

170
00:12:32,870 --> 00:12:33,870
from.

171
00:12:33,870 --> 00:12:39,639
By following trends and outsmarting the tricks
of institutional traders, you will too start

172
00:12:39,639 --> 00:12:42,450
seeing bigger gains.

173
00:12:42,450 --> 00:12:45,070
Just keep practicing spotting the patterns.

174
00:12:45,070 --> 00:12:52,050
Study old charts to compare tells of real
versus fake signals above or below moving

175
00:12:52,050 --> 00:12:53,100
averages.

176
00:12:53,100 --> 00:12:59,089
And most important, when you find another
liquidity run, above or below a previous key

177
00:12:59,089 --> 00:13:02,269
level, you have found the strongest signal.

178
00:13:02,269 --> 00:13:09,089
With experience, you'll get better and better
at differentiating between genuine trend changes

179
00:13:09,089 --> 00:13:12,209
and traps set by smart money.

180
00:13:12,209 --> 00:13:17,570
This strategy won’t work perfectly each
time, but it has served me well over the past

181
00:13:17,570 --> 00:13:18,570
months.

182
00:13:18,570 --> 00:13:20,709
There will always be ups and downs of course.

183
00:13:20,709 --> 00:13:27,269
But as long as you focus on the big picture
and remember your edge, you'll come out ahead

184
00:13:27,269 --> 00:13:29,149
more often than not.

185
00:13:29,149 --> 00:13:34,779
That's how I've succeeded trading moving average
breakouts - by recognizing these traps and

186
00:13:34,779 --> 00:13:38,740
turning them to my advantage instead of becoming
victim to them.

187
00:13:38,740 --> 00:13:38,820
Now it’s your turn!

